Large numbers
The Romans developed two main ways of writing large numbers, the apostrophus and the vinculum, further extended in various ways in later times.

Apostrophus
Using the apostrophus method, 500 is written as Iâ†ƒ, while 1,000 is written as CIâ†ƒ. This system of encasing numbers to denote thousands (imagine the Cs and â†ƒs as parentheses) had its origins in Etruscan numeral usage.
Each additional set of C and â†ƒ surrounding CIâ†ƒ raises the value by a factor of ten: CCIâ†ƒâ†ƒ represents 10,000 and CCCIâ†ƒâ†ƒâ†ƒ represents 100,000. Similarly, each additional â†ƒ to the right of Iâ†ƒ raises the value by a factor of ten: Iâ†ƒâ†ƒ represents 5,000 and Iâ†ƒâ†ƒâ†ƒ represents 50,000. Numerals larger than CCCIâ†ƒâ†ƒâ†ƒ do not occur.
